European debt write-off is unavoidable.
Berkeley — that's just the Greek crisis, that's just the Greek and Irish crises, people used to think that way, but now it can't be, because it's clearly a crisis of the eurozone.
It's easier to deal with than people typically expect, but also more difficult.
The economic logic of this crisis is quite straightforward.
The Greek's finances are problematic.
The Irish's banking industry is problematic.
The Portuguese's private debt market is problematic.
The Spanish's issues are across the aforementioned three aspects.
Despite the differences in detail, the conclusion is the same: these countries will all have to go through the painful process of cutting their spending.
It's typically necessary to combine domestic spending cuts and devaluation of the domestic currency to offset the side effects of the tightening policy.
Devaluation will enhance export competitiveness, which is essentially relying on foreign demand to make up for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone countries, they do not have their own currencies to devalue, so they can only rely on internal devaluation instead of external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to enhance export competitiveness, thereby achieving the effect of increasing foreign demand.
These crisis countries are indeed showing a strong commitment to tightening their belts.
However, one economic variable that has not changed along with the other variables is the debt of both the public and private sectors.
The face value of government accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt – aside from the debt owed to junior creditors – has remained largely unchanged.
It is this simple fact that puts the internal devaluation strategy at odds with itself: the more that wages and other costs are cut, the greater the burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The more the debt burden grows, the more it necessitates reducing public spending and increasing taxation to cope with government and its guardians' (such as banks) debt.
This in turn calls for even more internal devaluation, further exacerbating the debt burden, creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a quagmire of stagnation.
Therefore, in order for the internal devaluation strategy to be effective, a way must be found to reduce the nominal value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be restructured through debt-for-equity swaps, and banks that are insolvent should be liquidated.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
Policy makers are reluctant to take this route, which is understandable.
Contract sanctity is a matter of principle, but it cannot be allowed to stand in the way of necessary reforms.
The government is worried about losing credibility in the financial markets.
If creditors mainly come from abroad, especially foreign banks, a write-off will only harm other countries.
These concerns are not without basis, but they should not lead to an unreasonable conclusion.
The only viable options are internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose between the two.
They have ruled out the option of external devaluation.
However, internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this point is neither reasonable nor logical.
Debt restructuring's operation is straightforward.
The government can issue a batch of debt securities, with their face value discounted by a certain percentage from the existing debt face value.
Bondholders can choose to either stick to exchanging their bonds at face value, but with a later maturity date and lower interest rate; or accept a discounted bond with a lower face value than their existing bonds, but with an earlier maturity date and higher interest rate.
This is not cutting-edge technology; it has been done before.
However, to succeed, there are three prerequisites.
First, ensure the security of the new bonds to bondholders.
Someone needs to stand behind these bonds and guarantee them.
In the 1980s, when implementing the Brady Plan for Latin American debt restructuring, the U.S. Treasury Department played the role of "guarantor big brother".
Today, the International Monetary Fund and the German Government can take on that responsibility.
Second, countries must act in concert.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring will increase expectations among other countries, triggering a contagion effect.
Banks that suffer losses due to debt restructuring must have their balance sheets consolidated.
These banks need to undergo a real stress test, not the watered-down version they had earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals insolvency, a comprehensive debt-to-equity swap must be carried out for the relevant banks.
If this is not sufficient, the Government must intervene to inject capital into the relevant banks.
Countries must act in concert.
Once banks' balance sheets are consolidated, it is possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt and other private sector debt without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Let's discuss the biggest challenge now.
Decisive leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that their country's banks have a large exposure to debt in the eurozone's peripheral countries, and the situation is critical.
They must convince their backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it cannot shirk its responsibility to provide guarantees.
In one word, European leaders, especially German leaders, should paint a more dire picture – failure to do so will spell disaster.
Because that is the reality.
